724881f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 66th Street
724881f-a.text:
ROckefeller Institute for Medical Research, east of York Avenue from
o6th to o7th Streets. From right to left the builoings are: part
of the original laboratory (1906), Laboratory No. 2 (1916) and the
new laboratory, nearing completion, its south side in line with
o7th Street, which has been permanently closed east of York Avenue.
In the foreground are gardens and shelters for women and children.
July 31, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

1558291.title: East 66th Street - York Avenue
1558291.folder: East 66th Street - York Avenue, Manhattan, NY

724880f-b.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 66th Street
724880f-b.text:
(1)
York Avenue (Avenue A), east side, north from 66th Street. In the
right foreground are the grounds of the Rockefeller Institute,
which extend up to o7th Street. The block above, where the
Williams stone yards used to be around 1890-1900, is a children'a
playground.
On the N.W. corner of 68th Street is the old Central, an apartment
house built in 1902. East of it, on 68th Street, are the
stables and garage, and then the main plant, of the Central
Brewing Company, erected around 1900-02. In this block, prior
to about 1895, was Jones Woods Coliseum, known in its last
few years as Empire City Coliseum.
From 69th to 70th Streets may be seen old 1294-1304 Avenue A,
tenements built prior to 1910. From 70th to 71st Streets are
houses built, in their original form, from about 1890-V5, and
used for some years as cigar factories.
February 13, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
(2)
York Avenue, east side, north from 66th Street, the same view
as the preceding. The lamp post in the left foreground, in
both pictures, is on the N.W. corner of 66th Street.
Rockefeller Institute now has the entire property east of York
Avenue up to t8th Street. Notice their fence, with its stone
posts. The building to the north is the newest laboratory,
built in 1930.
The New York Hoapital and Cornell Medical College takes up the
entire three blocks from 6Bth to 71st Streets, and east to
Exterior Street, which is shortly to be rechristened Marie Curie
Avenue. The Bio-Chemistry and Pharmacy wing is located on the
very N.W. corner of 68th Street where the old Century apartment
house used to stand.
Compare these two views with Wurts Brothers' view of the same
acene early in 1V31.
March 5, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPROUUCTIONS.  TN3
PCDTC LEP
